commit.message:
Enhance lsvpd to use IPS version of output for serial number and processor ID

Currently, lsvpd prints values for serial number and processor ID using
system-id property in the device tree. Enhance lsvpd to print IPS
version for serial number and processor ID by checking if
ibm,vendor-system-id property exists in the device tree.  If it exists,
then use this to set the values for serial number and processor ID.
Else, use the existing method of fetching serial number and processor ID
from system-id property.

Signed-off-by: Sathvika Vasireddy <sv@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

Enhance lsvpd to use IPS version of output for machine type and model

Currently, lsvpd prints value for machine type and model using model
property in device tree. Enhance lsvpd to print IPS version for machine
type and model by checking if ibm,vendor-model property exists in the
device tree. If it exists, then use this to set the values for machine
type and model. Else, use the existing method of fetching machine type
and model values from model property.

Signed-off-by: Sathvika Vasireddy <sv@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

lscfg: Fix description mismatch for nvme devices

This patch addresses an issue in lscfg where there is a mismatch in
description values retrieved from two different sources for nvme devices.
The generic description fetched from the device-tree ibm,fw-adapter-name
file is incorrect, while the description fetched from the nvme f1h log
page is correct.

To resolve this inconsistency, this patch overwrites the generic
description value with the description value obtained from the nvme f1h
log page. By doing so, lscfg will display the correct description values
for nvme devices.

Without patch:

$ lscfg -vl 0563:20:00.0
  0563:20:00.0 nvme1 pci1014,6bb U50EE.001.WZS0011-P3-C3
                     800GB NVMe Gen4 II U.2 SSD (1014a825) <== (WRONG)
        Manufacturer Name.........IBM
        Machine Type-Model........NVMe SSD Controller PM173Xa
        Engineering Change Level..P65460
        Field Replaceable Unit Number
        ..........................02YC724
        Manufacturer ID...........S6RSNE0RA00654
        Part Number of assembly...01CM555
        Serial Number.............8CYFQ0RR
        Alterable ROM Level.......REV.SN66
        Device Specific.(ID)......800GB NVMe Gen4 U.2 SSD III <== (CORRECT)
        [...]

With patch:

$ ./lscfg -vl 0563:20:00.0
  0563:20:00.0 nvme1 pci1014,6bb U50EE.001.WZS0011-P3-C3
                     800GB NVMe Gen4 U.2 SSD III (1014a825)
        Manufacturer Name.........IBM
        Machine Type-Model........NVMe SSD Controller PM173Xa
        Engineering Change Level..P65460
        Field Replaceable Unit Number
        ..........................02YC724
        Manufacturer ID...........S6RSNE0RA00654
        Part Number of assembly...01CM555
        Serial Number.............8CYFQ0RR
        Alterable ROM Level.......REV.SN66
        Device Specific.(ID)......800GB NVMe Gen4 U.2 SSD III
        [...]

lsvpd: Update nvme_templates with logpage format for 0005 and 0006 versions

To collect nvme vpd data and set vpd fields accordingly, we interpret nvme
f1h logpage. Currently, there is support to interpret NVMe logpage versions
till 0004. NVMe devices with Alterable ROM Level REV.SN66 have f1h logpage
versions of 0005 and above. Since there is no support for 0005 and above
versions of nvme f1h logpage in the code yet, code returns without
interpreting logpage information, and hence nvme vpd data for such devices
are not being set and displayed completely. To address this issue, add nvme
template for f1h logpage versions 0005 and 0006.

Starting with Version 0005, a new value was added to Encryption field
(2 = BootROM support). And, starting with Version 0006, two new fields
(Reserved for Future DS8K Usage and DLFEAT PI Deviation Support) were added
to f1h logpage.

Before this patch:
$ lscfg -vl 05ed:70:00.0
  05ed:70:00.0 nvme0 pci1014,6bc U50EE.001.WZS005P-P3-C13
                                 1.6TB NVMe Gen4 II U.2 SSD (1014a825)
        Manufacturer Name.........IBM
        Machine Type-Model........NVMe SSD Controller PM173Xa
        Alterable ROM Level.......REV.SN66
        Device Specific.(YC)......0
        Location Code.(YL)........U50EE.001.WZS005P-P3-C13

After this patch:
$ lscfg -vl 05ed:70:00.0
  05ed:70:00.0 nvme0 pci1014,6bc U50EE.001.WZS005P-P3-C13
                                 1.6TB NVMe Gen4 II U.2 SSD (1014a825)

        Customer Card ID Number.(CC)
        ..........................5B52

        Device Specific.(Z1)......3.0
        Device Specific.(Z2)......1600

        Device Specific.(Z5)......02

commit.message:
lsvpd: Fill firmware information by recursively looking for firmware specific files within sysfs ID

Currently, fillFirmware() is filling firmware information based on the
classNode value of a given component. It then looks for firmware specific
sysfs files (fw_version, fwrev, firmware_rev), within the classNode path,
to set firmware fields accordingly. For components that do not have a
classNode value, fillFirmware() does not look for firmware information
within the sysfs firmware files, and hence does not set firmware fields.

This patch recursively looks for sysfs firmware files within the ID path of
a component, and sets the firmware fields accordingly, if not already set.

Reported-by: Borislav Stoymirski <borislav.stoymirski@bg.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Sathvika Vasireddy <sv@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

lsvpd/travis: Switch from Ubuntu20.04 to Ubuntu22.10

Starting with lsvpd version 1.7.14, there have been CI failures with
Ubuntu 20.04 docker container. lsvpd now depends on new libvpd library
version v2.2.9 which is not part of ubuntun 20.04 and hence the CI failures.

Ubuntu 22.10 ships the latest libvpd package which makes it perfect for
travis CI builds. Update .travis.yml file to force run docker commands
in a POWER9 VM as Ubuntu22.10 is supported only on POWER9 or newer
systems.

Also, update Dockerfile to install pkg-config package to fix existing
travis CI failures on Ubuntu.

Signed-off-by: Sathvika Vasireddy <sv@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Mahesh Salgaonkar <mahesh@linux.ibm.com>

vpdupdate: Use locking to prevent update race.

There are udev rules that may run vpdupdate multiple times in parallel.
With a number of processes reading/updating/archiving the database the
readers may see an inconsistent state. Lock the database file during
archival.

sysfstreecollector: Fix compiler warning

src/internal/sys_interface/sysfstreecollector.cpp: In member function 'std::__cxx11::string lsvpd::SysFSTreeCollector::getDevTreePath(std::__cxx11::string)':
src/internal/sys_interface/sysfstreecollector.cpp:981:12: warning: ignoring return value of 'char* realpath(const char*, char*)', declared with attribute warn_unused_result [-Wunused-result]

returns a pointer to buf2 so, if buf2 is NULL, so is the return value.

devicetreecollector: buildSCSI() - add support for SCSI loc-code

fillQuickVPD failing to find the loc-code, doesn't always attribute to
the missing device-tree entry associated with the sysfs device path.
There are also configurations like USB hubs, to which the SCSI devices
gets connected with special device-tree layout. A USB controller, that
supports both USB 3.0 and USB 2.0 devices will create two USB hubs for
communicating with devices. Where one hub controllers devices with
speeds ranging upto  480M (USB 2.0) and another for devices operating
at the  5000M (USB 3.0). The layout might be little complex when the
USB 3.0 devices are internal on board ones and 2.0 is an external
device.

                     root hub
                    /         \
           USB hub 1 (2.0)  USB hub 2 (3.0)
                   |         /            \
                 external   internal    internal
                  device    device1     device2

the populated device-tree adds both of the internal devices
under the hub1, that hosts the slower external device, with
the layout:
usb@1
|_ hub@1
   |_ cdrom@1 (USB 2.0)
   |_ usb-scsi@6 (USB 3.0, internal device 1)
   |_ usb-scsi@8 (USB 3.0, internal device 2)

this patch add support to find location code for such SCSI devices
connected to USB hubs in a mix and match of external and internal
devices.

Signed-off-by: Kamalesh Babulal <kamalesh@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Vasant Hegde <hegdevasant@linux.vnet.ibm.com>

sysfstreecollector: use of_node file to device-tree path

In getDevTreePath(), currently we read the devspec in the sysfs path of
the device to retrive the path represented in /proc/device-tree, some
modern device do not construct devspec file, instead relay on of_node
file, which is a symlink to a file in the device-tree.

Teach getDevTreePath() to check for of_node file, and read the symbolic
link it points too and in case of of_node not available, fall back to

Signed-off-by: Kamalesh Babulal <kamalesh@linux.ibm.com>
Signed-off-by: Vasant Hegde <hegdevasant@linux.vnet.ibm.com>

sysfstreecollector: check path before return in getDevTreePath()

devspec holds the device-path for the device in the /proc/device-tree,
some cases this file may also hold "(null)" string as value. Check for
device-tree path before returning from getDevTreePath() and return
empty string like in the error cases for "(null)" case.
